50|$|There {{are several}} types of {{performance}} guarantees, and one may often choose them à la carte, with higher risk charges for guarantees that are riskier for the insurance companies. The first type is a guaranteed minimum death benefit (GMDB), which can be received only if {{the owner of the}} <b>annuity</b> <b>contract,</b> or the covered annuitant, dies.|$|E
50|$|Stable value {{funds are}} {{structured}} {{in one of}} three ways: as a separately managed account, which is a stable value fund managed for one specific 401(k) plan; as a commingled fund, which pools together assets from many 401(k) plans and offers the benefits of diversification and economies of scale for smaller plans; or as a guaranteed insurance company account, which issues a group <b>annuity</b> <b>contract</b> directly to the plan.|$|E
